    <text>
        <body>
            <head>256. Paper Prepared in the <orgName corresp="rec7Bg5QUDG0eHqgl">Department of
                    State</orgName>
                <note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d256fn1">Source: Department of State,
                    Bureau of Arms Control and Disarmament, Lot 01D127, 1969–1990 Subject Records of
                    James P. <persName corresp="recoqpx2aNuHTDUHK">Timbie</persName>, Box 1, <gloss
                        target="#t_START_1">
                        <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recHvtjt4uCqCi2Qk">START</rs>
                    </gloss>/<gloss target="#t_INF_1">INF</gloss> 1987. Secret. A stamped notation
                    indicates that <persName corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName> saw the
                    paper. <persName corresp="recoqpx2aNuHTDUHK">Timbie</persName> sent the paper to
                        <persName corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName> under cover of a
                    December 31 note: “Some thoughts for the New Year on <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                        <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recHvtjt4uCqCi2Qk">START</rs>
                    </gloss>.” A stamped notation indicates that <persName
                        corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName> saw the note. (Ibid.)</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date
                        ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-editorial-annotation" calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1987-12-31">undated</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">
                <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recHvtjt4uCqCi2Qk">START</rs>
                </gloss>
            </p>
            <p>With the basic structure of a <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recHvtjt4uCqCi2Qk">START</rs>
                </gloss> Treaty now set, we face four major problems, all related to <rs
                    corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45" type="topic">verification</rs>:</p>
            <quote>
                <p>—How to verify the number of <rs type="topic" corresp="recInQ6JTYKBeryID"
                        >mobile</rs>
                    <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                        <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                    </gloss>;</p>
                <p>—How to verify the number of nuclear-armed <gloss target="#t_SLCM_1">
                        <rs corresp="recRMohN3AY0ch5I7" type="topic">SLCMs</rs>
                    </gloss>;</p>
                <p>—How to distinguish nuclear-armed <gloss target="#t_ALCM_1">
                        <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCMs</rs>
                    </gloss> from conventional <gloss target="#t_ALCM_1">
                        <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCMs</rs>
                    </gloss>;</p>
                <p>—What to propose in the <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                        <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recHvtjt4uCqCi2Qk">START</rs>
                    </gloss> Inspection Protocol.</p>
            </quote>
            <p>On one of these we are close to having a position to propose to the Soviets—the
                interagency <rs corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45" type="topic">verification</rs> group is
                working hard on a <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recHvtjt4uCqCi2Qk">START</rs>
                </gloss> Inspection Protocol with the objective of tabling it early in the next
                round, drawing upon the <gloss target="#t_INF_1">
                    <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="reclckIw9AgH05Yxw">INF</rs>
                </gloss> inspection protocol, the concepts agreed to in the <rs
                    type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recPOnzDG0FI16H1Y">Joint Statement</rs>,
                and the special requirements of <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recHvtjt4uCqCi2Qk">START</rs>
                </gloss>. On <rs type="topic" corresp="recInQ6JTYKBeryID">mobile</rs>
                <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                </gloss>’s work has been done in the Support Group to develop further the ideas that
                were once considered for counting <rs type="topic" corresp="recibQAICNR8y1pTK"
                    >SS–20</rs>’s, but we do not have a scheme which is judged to give us effective
                    <rs corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45" type="topic">verification</rs>; this effort will
                continue on a priority basis. <rs corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45" type="topic"
                    >Verification</rs> of <gloss target="#t_SLCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="recRMohN3AY0ch5I7" type="topic">SLCMs</rs>
                </gloss> and <gloss target="#t_ALCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCMs</rs>
                </gloss> will be taken up in January.</p>
            <p>In addition to the <rs corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45" type="topic">verification</rs>
                issues, there is another tier of problems, including the number of <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recInQ6JTYKBeryID">mobile</rs>
                <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                </gloss>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs> to be permitted, the
                range threshhold for <gloss target="#t_ALCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCMs</rs>
                </gloss>, the <gloss target="#t_ALCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCM</rs>
                </gloss>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recYq8ReZQ3bXtQu4">counting rule</rs>, <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="reclksm3VX3UUxetF">throw weight</rs> definition, and <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recPOh1SDhDLLFZPg">non-deployed missiles</rs>. Two more issues—<rs
                    corresp="recbybjw3iHkqwwou" type="topic">Backfire</rs> and heavy <gloss
                    target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                </gloss>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recbm2CDfl6YlSCnq">modernization</rs>—are not resolved
                with the Soviets but the summit NSDD<note n="2" place="foot" xml:id="d256fn2">See
                        <ref target="#d244">Document 244</ref>.</note> provides adequate guidance.
                Finally, the <orgName corresp="rechbJf4QHaXNGzWb">Delegation</orgName> will continue
                to push for a 3300 <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                </gloss> RV <rs type="topic" corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19">sublimit</rs>.</p>
            <p>Overall, we find ourselves in a position where the basic questions of the structure
                of the agreement, the key numbers, most of the <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recTaee7UxoGjTDrc">counting rules</rs>, and the <rs
                    corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45" type="topic">verification</rs> approach, which have
                been the center of attention since <rs type="event" corresp="recY5TBKXKBIuAnWc"
                    >Reykjavik</rs>, are now agreed. Many of the problems which now come to the fore
                have received relatively little attention, and it will take a major effort to
                develop our positions. There is much homework to be done.</p>
            <pb facs="1172" n="1145" xml:id="pg_1145"/>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">US <rs type="topic" corresp="recAynYh8uzxYGQRH"
                    >Strategic Force</rs> under <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recHvtjt4uCqCi2Qk">START</rs>
                </gloss>
            </p>
            <p>The principal criticism of <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recHvtjt4uCqCi2Qk">START</rs>
                </gloss> is that it would result in a more vulnerable US <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recAynYh8uzxYGQRH">strategic force</rs>. <persName
                    corresp="rectUrMkOWahA6Bv8">Kissinger</persName>, <persName
                    corresp="rec1BYpVimWguCga9">Scowcroft</persName>, Woolsey, and others hold up
                the specter of a US force consisting of a handful of submarines, a few bombers, and
                some vulnerable fixed <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                </gloss>. The structure of the agreement we are working out by no means requires
                this result. The best counter to these charges would be to put forward the sort of
                force we would intend to deploy under the <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recHvtjt4uCqCi2Qk">START</rs>
                </gloss> agreement. Such an exercise raises tricky questions, but is well worth
                doing.</p>
            <p>The small numbers of submarines that critics cite come from attributing 12 <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs> to each <rs
                    corresp="rec4JjRoQ2nVMNeaE" type="topic">Trident</rs> II missile and 24 missiles
                to each <rs corresp="rec4JjRoQ2nVMNeaE" type="topic">Trident</rs> submarine. The
                agreement at the summit to attribute 8 <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga"
                    >warheads</rs> to each <rs corresp="rec4JjRoQ2nVMNeaE" type="topic">Trident</rs>
                II missile increases the number of submarines by 50% [<hi rendition="simple_italic"
                    >less than 7 lines not declassified</hi>] (Note that the Soviets quote 4 for
                their latest <rs corresp="recnGcR0g6J7yKHTE" type="topic">SLBM</rs>, a sensible
                number in a reductions environment.) The point is we can have any number of
                submarines we want, and we should decide at least roughly what that number is and
                how we want to achieve it, and make sure the agreement preserves our option to move
                in that direction.</p>
            <p>As for <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                </gloss>, the <gloss target="#t_MX_2">
                    <rs corresp="rec99k2btquR4fVXS" type="topic">M–X</rs>
                </gloss> is now in favor as an inexpensive way to deploy large numbers of <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs>. The small <gloss
                    target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                </gloss> is on the chopping block, but with tight limits on <gloss target="#t_RV_1"
                    >RVs</gloss> it would make a lot of sense. A plausible number of <gloss
                    target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                </gloss>
                <gloss target="#t_RV_1">RVs</gloss> under <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recHvtjt4uCqCi2Qk">START</rs>
                </gloss> would be 1400. The force in the late 1990’s could consist of 50 <gloss
                    target="#t_MX_2">
                    <rs corresp="rec99k2btquR4fVXS" type="topic">M–X</rs>
                </gloss>, 100 <gloss target="#t_MM_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recJIrLOK12134vZd">MM</rs>
                </gloss>–III, and 600 small <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                </gloss> (some fixed, some <rs type="topic" corresp="recInQ6JTYKBeryID"
                >mobile</rs>). Many other combinations are possible; the small, single <gloss
                    target="#t_RV_1">RV</gloss>
                <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                </gloss> would make a major contribution by keeping the number of aim-points high,
                giving a portion of the <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                </gloss> force survivability through mobility, and replacing the <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recJIrLOK12134vZd">Minuteman</rs> II which will be 30 years old in the
                late 1990’s.</p>
            <p>Our <rs type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">bomber</rs> force could consist of
                100 <rs corresp="rec0V6EbHEqgh7tei" type="topic">B–1</rs>’s and 150 <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recJrKQ97ZB4lDj0t">stealth</rs> bombers, with 850 <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recJrKQ97ZB4lDj0t">stealth</rs>
                <gloss target="#t_ALCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCMs</rs>
                </gloss> deployed on the <rs corresp="rec0V6EbHEqgh7tei" type="topic"
                >B–1</rs>’s.</p>
            <p>Such a force would be far more survivable and effective than the ones postulated by
                    <persName corresp="rectUrMkOWahA6Bv8">Kissinger</persName>, <persName
                    corresp="rec1BYpVimWguCga9">Scowcroft</persName>, and the critics, and would fit
                well within the 6000, 4900, and 1600 limits of <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recHvtjt4uCqCi2Qk">START</rs>
                </gloss>. There is a natural resistance, especially in <gloss target="#t_JCS_1">
                    <orgName corresp="recYt5V8hImTp3Aah">JCS</orgName>
                </gloss>, to thinking now about how we would allocate the reductions between the
                services, but some thinking along lines can help us in deciding what options to
                preserve and in countering the main thrust of our critics.</p>
        </body>
    </text>
